La Graufesenque is an archaeological site 2km from Millau, Aveyron, France at the junction of the Tarn and Dourbie rivers.
As Condatomagus (market of the confluent) it was famous in the Gallo-Roman period for the production of high quality dark red terra sigillata pottery, which was made in vast quantities and exported over much of the western part of the Roman Empire.
Production of pottery started at La Graufesenque under the reign of Augustus.
